#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"A career change resume is fundamentally different from a traditional resume update. When you are switching careers, you cannot simply list your previous job titles and expect hiring managers to connect the dots. Instead, you need to strategically reframe your entire professional narrative to demonstrate relevance to your target field.\n"
"\n"
"The biggest mistake career changers make is using a chronological resume that emphasizes job titles and company names from their previous industry. This format immediately signals to recruiters that you are an outsider, and your resume may be dismissed before anyone reads past the first few lines. A career change resume must lead with value, not history.\n"
"\n"
"Research shows that recruiters spend an average of seven seconds on an initial resume scan. For career changers, this window is even more critical because you need to overcome the implicit bias against candidates from outside the industry. Your resume must immediately communicate that you understand the new field and bring unique value to it.\n"
"\n"
"The key is to shift from a responsibility-based resume to an achievement-based one. Rather than describing what you did in your previous role, focus on the outcomes you delivered and how those outcomes translate to the needs of your target industry. This reframing is not about being dishonest; it is about presenting the same experience through a different lens."
msgstr ""
"A career change resume is fundamentally different from a traditional resume update. When you are switching careers, you cannot simply list your previous job titles and expect hiring managers to connect the dots. Instead, you need to strategically reframe your entire professional narrative to demonstrate relevance to your target field.\n"
"\n"
"The biggest mistake career changers make is using a chronological resume that emphasizes job titles and company names from their previous industry. This format immediately signals to recruiters that you are an outsider, and your resume may be dismissed before anyone reads past the first few lines. A career change resume must lead with value, not history.\n"
"\n"
"Research shows that recruiters spend an average of seven seconds on an initial resume scan. For career changers, this window is even more critical because you need to overcome the implicit bias against candidates from outside the industry. Your resume must immediately communicate that you understand the new field and bring unique value to it.\n"
"\n"
"The key is to shift from a responsibility-based resume to an achievement-based one. Rather than describing what you did in your previous role, focus on the outcomes you delivered and how those outcomes translate to the needs of your target industry. This reframing is not about being dishonest; it is about presenting the same experience through a different lens."

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"A chronological resume is the most widely used resume format across industries and career levels. It organizes your professional experience in reverse chronological order, meaning your most recent position appears first and your earliest relevant role appears last. This format gives recruiters and hiring managers a clear, linear view of your career progression, making it easy to trace your professional growth over time.\n"
"\n"
"The chronological format is sometimes referred to as the \"reverse chronological resume\" because it inverts the natural timeline of your career. Instead of starting from the beginning, it leads with your current or most recent role, which is typically the most relevant to the position you are applying for. This structure mirrors how most hiring managers read resumes: they want to see what you have been doing recently and whether that experience aligns with their open position.\n"
"\n"
"At its core, a chronological resume emphasizes the trajectory of your career. It showcases upward mobility, increasing responsibility, and continuous employment. For professionals who have a steady work history without significant gaps, this format is the gold standard. It tells a compelling story of professional development that resonates with employers who value stability and growth.\n"
"\n"
"The chronological resume typically includes the following sections in order: contact information, a professional summary or objective, work experience listed in reverse chronological order, education, and optional sections such as certifications, volunteer work, or technical skills. The work experience section is the centerpiece, with each entry including your job title, employer name, dates of employment, and a list of achievements and responsibilities."
msgstr ""
"A chronological resume is the most widely used resume format across industries and career levels. It organizes your professional experience in reverse chronological order, meaning your most recent position appears first and your earliest relevant role appears last. This format gives recruiters and hiring managers a clear, linear view of your career progression, making it easy to trace your professional growth over time.\n"
"\n"
