"Typically, one to two rounds of counter-offers are considered normal and professional. Three or more rounds can start to feel adversarial and may erode goodwill. This is why it is important to make your first counter-offer thoughtful and well-researched rather than low-balling with the expectation of multiple rounds. Aim to make your first counter your best reasonable ask, leaving some room for compromise but not so much that you need extensive back-and-forth.\n"
"\n"
"The counter-offer window is usually three to five business days after receiving the initial offer, though this varies by company and urgency. If the employer has given you a deadline, respect it while ensuring you have enough time to evaluate the offer properly. If you need more time, it is perfectly acceptable to request an extension, especially if you are waiting on other opportunities."

#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid "A cover letter should be between 250 and 400 words, fitting on a single page. Aim for three to four well-crafted paragraphs that cover your introduction, key qualifications, and a strong closing with a call to action. Hiring managers typically spend less than a minute reviewing a cover letter, so conciseness is essential."
msgstr "A cover letter should be between 250 and 400 words, fitting on a single page. Aim for three to four well-crafted paragraphs that cover your introduction, key qualifications, and a strong closing with a call to action. Hiring managers typically spend less than a minute reviewing a cover letter, so conciseness is essential."

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"A creative resume can be a powerful differentiator in situations where visual presentation is not just appreciated but expected. The decision to use a creative format should be driven by a clear understanding of your target audience, the industry norms, and the specific role you are pursuing. When used appropriately, a creative resume signals that you understand design, branding, and visual communication, skills that are directly relevant to many professional roles.\n"
"\n"
"Creativity in a resume helps most when it serves a functional purpose. A well-designed infographic section that visualizes your skill proficiency levels, for example, communicates information more efficiently than a plain text list. A carefully chosen color scheme that reflects your personal brand can make your resume memorable without being distracting. The key is that every creative element should enhance the reader's understanding of your qualifications rather than obscure it.\n"
"\n"
"The context in which your resume will be reviewed also matters. If you are handing your resume directly to a hiring manager at a portfolio review or design meetup, a visually striking format can make an immediate impression. If you are submitting through an online portal that uses ATS filtering, the creative elements need to be balanced with structural compatibility. Understanding this distinction is essential to using creativity effectively.\n"
"\n"
"Creative resumes also help when you are applying to roles where your resume itself serves as a work sample. Graphic designers, UX designers, art directors, and marketing professionals are expected to demonstrate their design sensibility through everything they produce, including their resume. In these cases, a plain, text-only resume might actually work against you by suggesting a lack of creative skill or attention to visual detail.\n"
"\n"
"However, creativity should never come at the expense of clarity. A resume that is beautiful but difficult to read or navigate will frustrate the reviewer. The most effective creative resumes strike a balance between visual appeal and usability, ensuring that the information hierarchy is clear, the text is legible, and the overall layout guides the reader naturally through your qualifications."
