#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"A functional resume, also known as a skills-based resume, is a format that prioritizes your abilities, competencies, and transferable skills over your chronological work history. Instead of organizing your experience by employer and date, a functional resume groups your accomplishments under relevant skill categories. This approach shifts the focus from where and when you worked to what you can do and what you have achieved.\n"
"\n"
"The functional resume format emerged as an alternative for job seekers whose career trajectories do not follow a traditional linear path. While the chronological format works beautifully for someone who has spent 15 years climbing the ladder in a single industry, it can be a disadvantage for individuals who are changing careers, re-entering the workforce after a break, or whose most relevant experience is not their most recent. The functional format solves this problem by allowing you to lead with your strongest qualifications regardless of when or where you developed them.\n"
"\n"
"In a typical functional resume, you will find a contact information header, a professional summary or career objective, a core skills or competencies section organized into thematic categories, a brief work history section listing only job titles, employers, and dates, and an education section. The skills section is the focal point and may occupy the majority of the page. Each skill category includes specific examples and achievements that demonstrate your proficiency.\n"
"\n"
"It is worth noting that the functional resume format is the least common of the three major formats and is sometimes viewed with skepticism by recruiters. Some hiring managers associate it with candidates who are trying to hide something, such as employment gaps or a lack of direct experience. Understanding when and how to use this format effectively is crucial to avoiding these pitfalls and making a strong impression."
