#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid "A resume summary should be two to four sentences, typically 40 to 60 words. This length is enough to communicate your professional identity, core skills, and a standout achievement without overwhelming the reader. Keep it concise so recruiters can absorb the key points in a single glance."
msgstr "A resume summary should be two to four sentences, typically 40 to 60 words. This length is enough to communicate your professional identity, core skills, and a standout achievement without overwhelming the reader. Keep it concise so recruiters can absorb the key points in a single glance."

#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-sections.ts
msgid ""
"A resume summary, sometimes called a professional summary or resume profile, is a concise paragraph at the top of your resume that highlights your most relevant qualifications, experience, and accomplishments. Think of it as your elevator pitch on paper: you have roughly six seconds to convince a recruiter that the rest of your resume is worth reading, and the summary is where that impression forms.\n"
"\n"
"Unlike the outdated objective statement, which focuses on what you want from an employer, a resume summary focuses on what you bring to the table. It typically runs two to four sentences long and is tailored to the specific role you are targeting. The most effective summaries blend your years of experience, core competencies, and a measurable achievement into one compelling snapshot.\n"
"\n"
"Recruiters and applicant tracking systems both parse this section heavily. A well-written summary can boost your chances of passing initial screening by as much as 40 percent, according to multiple hiring manager surveys. It acts as an anchor that orients the reader and sets expectations for the detail that follows in your experience and skills sections."
