#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"A well-designed spreadsheet is the simplest and most flexible tracking tool available. Create columns for: company name, position title, job posting URL, date applied, application method (direct site, LinkedIn, referral, recruiter), contact person, email or phone, current status (applied, phone screen scheduled, interview scheduled, offer, rejected, no response), follow-up date, and notes.\n"
"\n"
"Add conditional formatting to make your tracker visually scannable at a glance. Color-code the status column so applied is yellow, interviews are green, rejections are red, and offers are blue. Add highlighting for follow-up dates that are today or overdue. These visual cues ensure you never miss an action item when reviewing your tracker.\n"
"\n"
"Include a separate tab for networking contacts that tracks the person's name, company, how you connected, date of last contact, what you discussed, and planned next steps. Many of your best leads will come through networking rather than direct applications, and tracking these relationships with the same rigor as job applications ensures you follow up appropriately and maintain the relationships that generate opportunities.\n"
"\n"
"Create a third tab for interview preparation that logs interview dates, interviewers, questions asked, your responses, and post-interview reflections. This interview journal helps you identify patterns in the questions you receive, improve your responses over time, and remember details that are relevant for follow-up communications and subsequent interview rounds.\n"
"\n"
"Review your tracker at the start and end of each search day. The morning review tells you what follow-ups are due and which applications need attention. The evening review ensures all of the day's activities are logged and tomorrow's priorities are clear. This five-minute habit at each end of the day prevents the information gaps that derail an organized search."
