#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"As job boards have grown, so has the prevalence of fraudulent and misleading postings. Learning to identify and avoid scams protects your time, personal information, and potentially your finances. Common red flags include positions that promise unrealistic pay, require upfront payment for training or supplies, use vague company names, or communicate exclusively through personal email addresses or messaging apps.\n"
"\n"
"Ghost postings, where companies list positions they have no intention of filling, are increasingly common. These postings may be kept active to build a talent pipeline, satisfy internal policies requiring external posting for positions already filled internally, or gather market intelligence about available talent. If a posting has been active for more than 60 days without updates, it may be a ghost posting.\n"
"\n"
"Verify the legitimacy of any posting by cross-referencing it with the company's official career page. If the position appears on Indeed but not on the company's website, it may have been posted by a third-party recruiter without authorization or may be fraudulent. Legitimate employers almost always post positions on their own career pages.\n"
"\n"
"Be cautious with postings that request sensitive personal information, such as Social Security numbers, bank account details, or copies of identification, early in the application process. No legitimate employer needs this information before an interview, and often not until after a formal offer has been extended. If a company requests sensitive data upfront, this is a strong indicator of a phishing scam.\n"
"\n"
"Use job board reporting features to flag suspicious postings. Most major platforms have mechanisms for users to report fraudulent listings, and reporting helps protect other job seekers. If you believe you have been targeted by a job scam, report it to the Federal Trade Commission and your state's attorney general's office in addition to the job board platform."
msgstr ""
"As job boards have grown, so has the prevalence of fraudulent and misleading postings. Learning to identify and avoid scams protects your time, personal information, and potentially your finances. Common red flags include positions that promise unrealistic pay, require upfront payment for training or supplies, use vague company names, or communicate exclusively through personal email addresses or messaging apps.\n"
"\n"
"Ghost postings, where companies list positions they have no intention of filling, are increasingly common. These postings may be kept active to build a talent pipeline, satisfy internal policies requiring external posting for positions already filled internally, or gather market intelligence about available talent. If a posting has been active for more than 60 days without updates, it may be a ghost posting.\n"
"\n"
"Verify the legitimacy of any posting by cross-referencing it with the company's official career page. If the position appears on Indeed but not on the company's website, it may have been posted by a third-party recruiter without authorization or may be fraudulent. Legitimate employers almost always post positions on their own career pages.\n"
"\n"
"Be cautious with postings that request sensitive personal information, such as Social Security numbers, bank account details, or copies of identification, early in the application process. No legitimate employer needs this information before an interview, and often not until after a formal offer has been extended. If a company requests sensitive data upfront, this is a strong indicator of a phishing scam.\n"
"\n"
"Use job board reporting features to flag suspicious postings. Most major platforms have mechanisms for users to report fraudulent listings, and reporting helps protect other job seekers. If you believe you have been targeted by a job scam, report it to the Federal Trade Commission and your state's attorney general's office in addition to the job board platform."

