#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"Before opening a single job board, define what you are looking for with specificity. Vague goals like \"a better job\" or \"something in marketing\" lead to scattered applications and difficulty evaluating opportunities. Instead, define your target role title, industry, company size, geographic requirements, compensation range, and non-negotiable criteria.\n"
"\n"
"Create a prioritized list of criteria using a must-have, nice-to-have, and dealbreaker framework. Must-haves are non-negotiable requirements like minimum salary, geographic location, or remote work options. Nice-to-haves are preferences that would make an opportunity more attractive, such as specific technologies, company culture attributes, or growth paths. Dealbreakers are conditions that would cause you to decline regardless of other factors, such as excessive travel or specific ethical concerns.\n"
"\n"
"Set quantitative targets for your search activities. For example, aim to submit five to ten tailored applications per week, make three to five networking connections, attend one to two industry events or informational interviews, and follow up on all pending applications weekly. These targets ensure consistent effort and create accountability even during periods when motivation is low.\n"
"\n"
"Define your timeline realistically. The average job search takes two to six months depending on industry, level, and market conditions. Setting a realistic timeline helps you pace your effort and manage your finances appropriately. If you are searching while employed, a longer timeline may be acceptable. If you are unemployed, a more aggressive pace with daily dedicated search hours is appropriate.\n"
"\n"
"Review and adjust your goals every two to three weeks based on what you are learning from the market. If you are getting zero responses to applications in a specific industry, it may be time to broaden your criteria or adjust your approach. If you are getting interviews but no offers, the issue may be in your interview preparation rather than your application strategy."
msgstr ""
"Before opening a single job board, define what you are looking for with specificity. Vague goals like \"a better job\" or \"something in marketing\" lead to scattered applications and difficulty evaluating opportunities. Instead, define your target role title, industry, company size, geographic requirements, compensation range, and non-negotiable criteria.\n"
