#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"Building an effective combination resume requires careful planning and a clear understanding of how each section serves your overall narrative. Start with your contact information at the top, followed by a professional summary of three to five sentences that encapsulates your career identity, key strengths, and the value you bring to a potential employer.\n"
"\n"
"The core competencies or skills section comes next and is the defining feature of the combination format. Organize your skills into three to five thematic categories that align with the requirements of your target role. Under each category, include two to four bullet points that provide specific evidence of your capability. These bullets should be achievement-oriented and quantified whenever possible. For example, under \"Strategic Planning,\" you might include \"designed and implemented a three-year growth strategy that resulted in 40% revenue increase and expansion into two new markets.\"\n"
"\n"
"Following the skills section, present your work experience in reverse chronological order. Each entry should include your job title, employer name, location, and dates of employment. Because your key accomplishments are already detailed in the skills section, you can be more concise here. Include two to four bullet points per role that provide additional context or highlight achievements that did not fit into your skill categories. Focus on results that demonstrate your impact in each specific role.\n"
"\n"
"Your education section comes after work experience. Include degrees, institutions, graduation dates, and any notable honors or relevant coursework. For professionals with significant experience, education is typically a supporting section rather than a primary one.\n"
"\n"
"Optional sections such as certifications, technical proficiencies, languages, publications, or professional affiliations can follow education. These should be included only if they add tangible value to your candidacy. A certification that is directly relevant to the role can be a significant differentiator, while one that is tangential may just add clutter.\n"
"\n"
"The overall length of your combination resume should be one to two pages. The skills section and work experience should be roughly balanced in terms of page real estate. If your skills section takes up 60 percent of the first page and your work history is squeezed into the remaining space, the resume may feel unbalanced. Aim for a harmonious layout that gives both sections adequate room to make their case."
msgstr ""
"Building an effective combination resume requires careful planning and a clear understanding of how each section serves your overall narrative. Start with your contact information at the top, followed by a professional summary of three to five sentences that encapsulates your career identity, key strengths, and the value you bring to a potential employer.\n"
"\n"
"The core competencies or skills section comes next and is the defining feature of the combination format. Organize your skills into three to five thematic categories that align with the requirements of your target role. Under each category, include two to four bullet points that provide specific evidence of your capability. These bullets should be achievement-oriented and quantified whenever possible. For example, under \"Strategic Planning,\" you might include \"designed and implemented a three-year growth strategy that resulted in 40% revenue increase and expansion into two new markets.\"\n"
"\n"
"Following the skills section, present your work experience in reverse chronological order. Each entry should include your job title, employer name, location, and dates of employment. Because your key accomplishments are already detailed in the skills section, you can be more concise here. Include two to four bullet points per role that provide additional context or highlight achievements that did not fit into your skill categories. Focus on results that demonstrate your impact in each specific role.\n"
"\n"
"Your education section comes after work experience. Include degrees, institutions, graduation dates, and any notable honors or relevant coursework. For professionals with significant experience, education is typically a supporting section rather than a primary one.\n"
"\n"
"Optional sections such as certifications, technical proficiencies, languages, publications, or professional affiliations can follow education. These should be included only if they add tangible value to your candidacy. A certification that is directly relevant to the role can be a significant differentiator, while one that is tangential may just add clutter.\n"
"\n"
"The overall length of your combination resume should be one to two pages. The skills section and work experience should be roughly balanced in terms of page real estate. If your skills section takes up 60 percent of the first page and your work history is squeezed into the remaining space, the resume may feel unbalanced. Aim for a harmonious layout that gives both sections adequate room to make their case."

#: src/data/wiki/categories/networking-linkedin.ts
msgid ""
"Building an online presence is an ongoing process that benefits from measurement and iteration. Track key metrics to understand what is working and where you need to invest more effort. On LinkedIn, monitor profile views, search appearances, and post engagement weekly. On your personal website, install analytics to track visitors, page views, traffic sources, and the specific content that attracts the most attention.\n"
"\n"
"Set benchmarks based on your starting point and realistic growth expectations. If your LinkedIn profile currently receives ten views per week, aim to reach fifty within three months through headline optimization, consistent posting, and network expansion. If your personal website receives zero organic traffic, aim for one hundred monthly visitors within six months by publishing SEO-optimized articles targeting keywords in your professional niche.\n"
"\n"
"Experiment with different content types, posting times, and topics to discover what resonates with your audience. LinkedIn posts published on Tuesday through Thursday mornings tend to receive the highest engagement, but your specific audience may differ. Test short-form versus long-form content, personal stories versus professional insights, and text posts versus posts with images or carousels. Use the data to double down on what works and abandon what does not.\n"
"\n"
"Seek feedback from trusted colleagues and mentors about your online presence. Ask them to review your LinkedIn profile, personal website, and recent content with fresh eyes. They may identify blind spots, inconsistencies, or missed opportunities that you have overlooked. A third-party perspective is invaluable because you are too close to your own brand to evaluate it objectively. Incorporate their feedback and reassess your online presence quarterly to ensure it continues to evolve with your career."
msgstr ""
"Building an online presence is an ongoing process that benefits from measurement and iteration. Track key metrics to understand what is working and where you need to invest more effort. On LinkedIn, monitor profile views, search appearances, and post engagement weekly. On your personal website, install analytics to track visitors, page views, traffic sources, and the specific content that attracts the most attention.\n"
"\n"
"Set benchmarks based on your starting point and realistic growth expectations. If your LinkedIn profile currently receives ten views per week, aim to reach fifty within three months through headline optimization, consistent posting, and network expansion. If your personal website receives zero organic traffic, aim for one hundred monthly visitors within six months by publishing SEO-optimized articles targeting keywords in your professional niche.\n"
"\n"
"Experiment with different content types, posting times, and topics to discover what resonates with your audience. LinkedIn posts published on Tuesday through Thursday mornings tend to receive the highest engagement, but your specific audience may differ. Test short-form versus long-form content, personal stories versus professional insights, and text posts versus posts with images or carousels. Use the data to double down on what works and abandon what does not.\n"
"\n"
"Seek feedback from trusted colleagues and mentors about your online presence. Ask them to review your LinkedIn profile, personal website, and recent content with fresh eyes. They may identify blind spots, inconsistencies, or missed opportunities that you have overlooked. A third-party perspective is invaluable because you are too close to your own brand to evaluate it objectively. Incorporate their feedback and reassess your online presence quarterly to ensure it continues to evolve with your career."

