#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"Company culture is the most important factor in day-to-day job satisfaction, yet it is the hardest to assess from the outside. Start with Glassdoor reviews, which provide unfiltered employee perspectives on management quality, work-life balance, compensation, career growth, and cultural values. Read at least 15 to 20 reviews to identify consistent themes rather than reacting to individual positive or negative experiences.\n"
"\n"
"Pay attention to the sentiment of reviews over time. A company with recent negative reviews after years of positive ones may be experiencing a cultural shift due to new leadership, rapid growth, or financial pressure. Conversely, a company with improving reviews may be successfully addressing past issues. The trajectory matters as much as the current average rating.\n"
"\n"
"LinkedIn provides valuable cultural signals through employee profiles. Look at the average tenure, the backgrounds of people in your target role, and the career paths of former employees. High turnover in a specific department may indicate management issues. Former employees who moved to prestigious companies suggest the experience is valued in the market. A team filled with recent hires may indicate rapid growth or instability.\n"
"\n"
"The company's social media presence, blog, and PR communications reveal the culture they aspire to project. While these are curated representations, they still contain useful information about values, priorities, and tone. A company that highlights employee achievements, community involvement, and work-life balance on its social channels is at least signaling that these things matter to their employer brand.\n"
"\n"
"Best Companies lists from Fortune, Glassdoor, Great Place to Work, and industry publications provide external validation of company culture. While no list is perfect, companies that consistently appear across multiple rankings are more likely to have genuinely positive cultures than companies that appear on none."
msgstr ""
"Company culture is the most important factor in day-to-day job satisfaction, yet it is the hardest to assess from the outside. Start with Glassdoor reviews, which provide unfiltered employee perspectives on management quality, work-life balance, compensation, career growth, and cultural values. Read at least 15 to 20 reviews to identify consistent themes rather than reacting to individual positive or negative experiences.\n"
"\n"
"Pay attention to the sentiment of reviews over time. A company with recent negative reviews after years of positive ones may be experiencing a cultural shift due to new leadership, rapid growth, or financial pressure. Conversely, a company with improving reviews may be successfully addressing past issues. The trajectory matters as much as the current average rating.\n"
"\n"
"LinkedIn provides valuable cultural signals through employee profiles. Look at the average tenure, the backgrounds of people in your target role, and the career paths of former employees. High turnover in a specific department may indicate management issues. Former employees who moved to prestigious companies suggest the experience is valued in the market. A team filled with recent hires may indicate rapid growth or instability.\n"
"\n"
"The company's social media presence, blog, and PR communications reveal the culture they aspire to project. While these are curated representations, they still contain useful information about values, priorities, and tone. A company that highlights employee achievements, community involvement, and work-life balance on its social channels is at least signaling that these things matter to their employer brand.\n"
"\n"
"Best Companies lists from Fortune, Glassdoor, Great Place to Work, and industry publications provide external validation of company culture. While no list is perfect, companies that consistently appear across multiple rankings are more likely to have genuinely positive cultures than companies that appear on none."

