#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"Depending on the length of your career break, the professional landscape in your field may have evolved. Technologies change, best practices shift, and new tools emerge. Demonstrating that you are current is essential for a successful return.\n"
"\n"
"Start by researching what has changed in your industry since you stepped away. Read industry publications, follow thought leaders on social media, and review recent job postings for roles similar to your target position. Pay attention to new tools, technologies, methodologies, and buzzwords that appear frequently. This research will help you identify specific areas where you need to update your knowledge.\n"
"\n"
"Online courses and certifications are the fastest way to close knowledge gaps and signal to employers that you are up to date. Many reputable platforms offer courses that can be completed in days or weeks. Choose courses that provide a certificate upon completion, as these give you tangible credentials to add to your resume.\n"
"\n"
"Attend industry events, webinars, and conferences to immerse yourself in the current state of your field. These events are also excellent networking opportunities. Reconnect with former colleagues and mentors, and build new professional relationships. Many people find their return-to-work opportunity through their network rather than through job postings.\n"
"\n"
"Consider joining a returnship program if one is available in your industry. Major companies like Goldman Sachs, IBM, and Amazon have formal programs designed specifically for professionals returning after career breaks. These programs typically last 12 to 16 weeks and offer structured reentry with mentorship, training, and a clear path to a permanent position."
msgstr ""
"Depending on the length of your career break, the professional landscape in your field may have evolved. Technologies change, best practices shift, and new tools emerge. Demonstrating that you are current is essential for a successful return.\n"
"\n"
"Start by researching what has changed in your industry since you stepped away. Read industry publications, follow thought leaders on social media, and review recent job postings for roles similar to your target position. Pay attention to new tools, technologies, methodologies, and buzzwords that appear frequently. This research will help you identify specific areas where you need to update your knowledge.\n"
"\n"
"Online courses and certifications are the fastest way to close knowledge gaps and signal to employers that you are up to date. Many reputable platforms offer courses that can be completed in days or weeks. Choose courses that provide a certificate upon completion, as these give you tangible credentials to add to your resume.\n"
"\n"
"Attend industry events, webinars, and conferences to immerse yourself in the current state of your field. These events are also excellent networking opportunities. Reconnect with former colleagues and mentors, and build new professional relationships. Many people find their return-to-work opportunity through their network rather than through job postings.\n"
"\n"
"Consider joining a returnship program if one is available in your industry. Major companies like Goldman Sachs, IBM, and Amazon have formal programs designed specifically for professionals returning after career breaks. These programs typically last 12 to 16 weeks and offer structured reentry with mentorship, training, and a clear path to a permanent position."

