#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"Effective creative resume design follows the same fundamental principles that govern all good visual communication. Typography is perhaps the most impactful design element. Choose no more than two complementary typefaces: one for headings and one for body text. Ensure that your body text is at least 10 to 11 points in size for print readability and that your heading hierarchy is clear and consistent. Avoid decorative fonts for body text, as they reduce readability and can feel unprofessional.\n"
"\n"
"Color should be used strategically and sparingly. A one- or two-color accent scheme is typically more effective than a rainbow of colors. Choose colors that reflect your personal brand and the industry you are targeting. Blues and greens convey professionalism and trustworthiness. Bold colors like orange or magenta can signal creativity and energy. Ensure sufficient contrast between text and background for readability, and test your resume in grayscale to confirm it remains effective when printed in black and white.\n"
"\n"
"White space, also known as negative space, is one of the most powerful tools in visual design. Generous margins, consistent spacing between sections, and breathing room around text blocks make your resume feel organized and inviting. Overcrowding a creative resume with too many elements, colors, or text blocks defeats the purpose of the creative format and makes the document feel chaotic.\n"
"\n"
"Visual hierarchy guides the reader's eye through your resume in the order you intend. Use size, weight, color, and position to establish a clear hierarchy. Your name and professional title should be the most prominent elements. Section headings should be clearly differentiated from body text. Important achievements or skills can be highlighted with subtle visual treatments such as bold text, color accents, or icons.\n"
"\n"
"If you include visual elements such as skill bars, icons, charts, or infographics, ensure they are accurate and meaningful. A skill bar showing your proficiency at 85% in Python is only useful if it reflects reality and the reader understands what the scale represents. Avoid purely decorative elements that consume space without conveying information. Every visual element on your resume should earn its place by communicating something about your qualifications.\n"
"\n"
"Consistency is the hallmark of professional design. Ensure that all elements of your resume follow the same stylistic conventions. If you use rounded corners on one graphic element, use them on all similar elements. If your icons are outlined rather than filled, maintain that style throughout. Inconsistencies in design suggest carelessness, which contradicts the message of visual competence that a creative resume is meant to convey."
