#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"Effective follow-up is a strategic communication, not a pestering tactic. The goal is to demonstrate continued interest, provide additional value, and keep your name top of mind without being annoying. The line between persistent and pushy depends entirely on your timing, tone, and the value you add with each touchpoint.\n"
"\n"
"After submitting an application, wait seven to ten business days before your first follow-up. Send a brief email to the hiring manager or recruiter expressing continued interest and offering to provide any additional information. If you can find a relevant connection or talking point, such as a recent company achievement or industry development, weave it in to demonstrate ongoing engagement.\n"
"\n"
"After an interview, send a thank-you email within 24 hours to each person you spoke with. Personalize each email by referencing a specific topic from your conversation. This is not just politeness but a strategic opportunity to reinforce your qualifications, address anything you wish you had said during the interview, and demonstrate your communication skills.\n"
"\n"
"If the employer gave you a timeline for their decision, follow up one to two business days after that deadline passes. A simple message like \"I wanted to check in on the timeline for the X position. I remain very interested and am happy to provide any additional information that would be helpful\" is professional and appropriate. If no timeline was given, follow up one week after the interview.\n"
"\n"
"Track every follow-up in your system with the date sent and the response received. Limit yourself to two to three follow-ups per application before moving it to a \"no response\" status. If three follow-ups over several weeks receive no response, the silence is itself a response, and your energy is better spent on active opportunities. Keep these contacts in your tracker in case the company reaches out later, which happens more often than you might expect."
msgstr ""
"Effective follow-up is a strategic communication, not a pestering tactic. The goal is to demonstrate continued interest, provide additional value, and keep your name top of mind without being annoying. The line between persistent and pushy depends entirely on your timing, tone, and the value you add with each touchpoint.\n"
