#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid "Engineering Resume: Technical Resume Writing Guide"
msgstr "Engineering Resume: Technical Resume Writing Guide"

#: src/data/wiki/categories/industry-guides.ts
msgid ""
"Engineering resumes operate in a fundamentally different context than most other professional resumes. Technical hiring involves multiple evaluation stages, often including automated screening by applicant tracking systems configured with specific keyword filters, initial review by non-technical recruiters who rely on pattern matching, and deep evaluation by engineering managers or senior engineers who scrutinize technical depth and problem-solving ability. Your resume must satisfy all three audiences simultaneously, which requires a careful balance of accessibility and technical precision.\n"
"\n"
"The engineering job market is also uniquely competitive in terms of skills specificity. A job posting for a senior backend engineer might list fifteen to twenty specific technologies, frameworks, and methodologies. While no candidate is expected to match every requirement, your resume must clearly demonstrate proficiency in the core technologies and willingness to learn adjacent ones. Unlike industries where transferable skills are broadly accepted, engineering roles often require demonstrated experience with specific tools, and your resume must make these matches immediately visible.\n"
"\n"
"Another distinguishing factor is the emphasis on building and shipping. Engineering managers care less about your job titles and more about what you built, how you built it, what challenges you overcame, and what impact your work had on users, systems, or business outcomes. This means your resume should read more like a portfolio of accomplishments than a list of responsibilities. Every bullet point should answer the question: what did you create, improve, or solve, and how did it matter?"
msgstr ""
"Engineering resumes operate in a fundamentally different context than most other professional resumes. Technical hiring involves multiple evaluation stages, often including automated screening by applicant tracking systems configured with specific keyword filters, initial review by non-technical recruiters who rely on pattern matching, and deep evaluation by engineering managers or senior engineers who scrutinize technical depth and problem-solving ability. Your resume must satisfy all three audiences simultaneously, which requires a careful balance of accessibility and technical precision.\n"
"\n"
"The engineering job market is also uniquely competitive in terms of skills specificity. A job posting for a senior backend engineer might list fifteen to twenty specific technologies, frameworks, and methodologies. While no candidate is expected to match every requirement, your resume must clearly demonstrate proficiency in the core technologies and willingness to learn adjacent ones. Unlike industries where transferable skills are broadly accepted, engineering roles often require demonstrated experience with specific tools, and your resume must make these matches immediately visible.\n"
"\n"
"Another distinguishing factor is the emphasis on building and shipping. Engineering managers care less about your job titles and more about what you built, how you built it, what challenges you overcame, and what impact your work had on users, systems, or business outcomes. This means your resume should read more like a portfolio of accomplishments than a list of responsibilities. Every bullet point should answer the question: what did you create, improve, or solve, and how did it matter?"

