#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"Even experienced professionals make avoidable mistakes in their cover letters. Being aware of these pitfalls will help you produce a polished final product. The most damaging error is sending a generic, one-size-fits-all letter. Hiring managers can immediately tell when a letter was not written for their specific role, and it signals a lack of genuine interest.\n"
"\n"
"Another frequent mistake is focusing too much on what you want rather than what you can offer. Phrases like \"I am looking for an opportunity to grow my skills\" center the letter on your needs rather than the employer's. Reframe these as value propositions: \"My background in data analytics will enable me to immediately contribute to your team's efforts to optimize supply chain performance.\"\n"
"\n"
"Typos and grammatical errors are a silent killer of cover letter effectiveness. A single error can undermine your credibility, especially for roles that require strong written communication. Always proofread your letter multiple times, read it aloud to catch awkward phrasing, and have a trusted colleague review it before submission. Tools like grammar checkers can help, but they are not a substitute for careful human review.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid excessively formal or stilted language. Phrases like \"I humbly submit my application for your esteemed consideration\" feel outdated and create distance between you and the reader. Write in a natural, conversational tone that still maintains professionalism. Imagine you are writing to a respected colleague, not a member of royalty.\n"
"\n"
"Finally, never apologize for what you lack. Statements like \"Although I do not have experience in project management...\" immediately highlight a weakness. Instead, focus on transferable skills and your eagerness to learn: \"My experience coordinating cross-departmental initiatives has given me a strong foundation in the project management principles required for this role.\""
msgstr ""
"Even experienced professionals make avoidable mistakes in their cover letters. Being aware of these pitfalls will help you produce a polished final product. The most damaging error is sending a generic, one-size-fits-all letter. Hiring managers can immediately tell when a letter was not written for their specific role, and it signals a lack of genuine interest.\n"
"\n"
"Another frequent mistake is focusing too much on what you want rather than what you can offer. Phrases like \"I am looking for an opportunity to grow my skills\" center the letter on your needs rather than the employer's. Reframe these as value propositions: \"My background in data analytics will enable me to immediately contribute to your team's efforts to optimize supply chain performance.\"\n"
"\n"
