"\n"
"Avoid excessively formal or stilted language. Phrases like \"I humbly submit my application for your esteemed consideration\" feel outdated and create distance between you and the reader. Write in a natural, conversational tone that still maintains professionalism. Imagine you are writing to a respected colleague, not a member of royalty.\n"
"\n"
"Finally, never apologize for what you lack. Statements like \"Although I do not have experience in project management...\" immediately highlight a weakness. Instead, focus on transferable skills and your eagerness to learn: \"My experience coordinating cross-departmental initiatives has given me a strong foundation in the project management principles required for this role.\""

#: src/data/wiki/categories/salary-negotiation.ts
msgid "Even when you need the job, you can still negotiate without risk. Focus on expressing enthusiasm first, then make a modest, well-researched ask. Something like \"I am very excited to accept and want to make this work. Would there be any flexibility to move the base to X, which aligns more closely with the market midpoint?\" This approach is low-risk and can still yield meaningful results."
msgstr "Even when you need the job, you can still negotiate without risk. Focus on expressing enthusiasm first, then make a modest, well-researched ask. Something like \"I am very excited to accept and want to make this work. Would there be any flexibility to move the base to X, which aligns more closely with the market midpoint?\" This approach is low-risk and can still yield meaningful results."

#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"Even with the best intentions, career changers often make mistakes that undermine their candidacy. Understanding these pitfalls can help you create a more effective resume.\n"
"\n"
"The most common mistake is failing to tailor your resume to the specific job you are applying for. A generic career change resume that tries to appeal to every possible employer will resonate with none of them. Each application should be customized to highlight the specific skills and experiences most relevant to that particular role.\n"
"\n"
"Another frequent error is over-explaining your career change in the resume itself. Your resume is a marketing document, not a confessional. Save the detailed explanation of why you are changing careers for your cover letter or interview. On the resume, simply present yourself as a qualified candidate for the role.\n"
"\n"
"Many career changers also make the mistake of devaluing their previous experience. Your years in another field are not wasted time; they are a unique asset. The cross-industry perspective you bring can lead to innovative solutions that someone who has spent their entire career in one field might never consider. Frame your diverse background as a strength, not a liability.\n"
"\n"
"Finally, do not neglect the visual presentation of your resume. Career changers sometimes focus so heavily on content that they overlook formatting, readability, and design. A clean, professional layout signals attention to detail and professionalism, qualities that are important in any field. Use a modern resume template that balances visual appeal with ATS compatibility."
msgstr ""
"Even with the best intentions, career changers often make mistakes that undermine their candidacy. Understanding these pitfalls can help you create a more effective resume.\n"
"\n"
"The most common mistake is failing to tailor your resume to the specific job you are applying for. A generic career change resume that tries to appeal to every possible employer will resonate with none of them. Each application should be customized to highlight the specific skills and experiences most relevant to that particular role.\n"
"\n"
"Another frequent error is over-explaining your career change in the resume itself. Your resume is a marketing document, not a confessional. Save the detailed explanation of why you are changing careers for your cover letter or interview. On the resume, simply present yourself as a qualified candidate for the role.\n"
"\n"
"Many career changers also make the mistake of devaluing their previous experience. Your years in another field are not wasted time; they are a unique asset. The cross-industry perspective you bring can lead to innovative solutions that someone who has spent their entire career in one field might never consider. Frame your diverse background as a strength, not a liability.\n"
"\n"
"Finally, do not neglect the visual presentation of your resume. Career changers sometimes focus so heavily on content that they overlook formatting, readability, and design. A clean, professional layout signals attention to detail and professionalism, qualities that are important in any field. Use a modern resume template that balances visual appeal with ATS compatibility."

