#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"Identifying your transferable skills requires honest self-reflection and a systematic approach. Many professionals underestimate the breadth of their transferable skills because these abilities feel so natural that they do not recognize them as distinct competencies.\n"
"\n"
"Start with a comprehensive job audit. Review every position you have held and list every task, responsibility, and achievement. Do not filter based on what you think is relevant to your target career; write down everything. Once you have a complete list, categorize each item by the underlying skill it represents. \"Created monthly sales reports\" becomes \"data analysis and reporting.\" \"Mediated disputes between team members\" becomes \"conflict resolution and interpersonal communication.\"\n"
"\n"
"Ask colleagues, mentors, and friends what they see as your strongest professional abilities. Others often recognize strengths that you take for granted. A manager might tell you that your greatest asset is your ability to simplify complex information for diverse audiences, a skill you never consciously developed but one that is highly valued in fields like technical writing, user experience design, and product management.\n"
"\n"
"Use job descriptions in your target field as a reverse-engineering tool. Read through 15 to 20 postings for roles you are interested in and identify the recurring skills they mention. Then map each of those skills back to your own experience. You will likely find that you already possess many of the requested competencies; you simply have not been framing them in the right language.\n"
"\n"
"Consider taking a formal skills assessment or working with a career coach. Tools like the CliftonStrengths assessment, the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator, or the DISC assessment can provide structured insights into your natural abilities and help you articulate them more effectively on your resume."
msgstr ""
"Identifying your transferable skills requires honest self-reflection and a systematic approach. Many professionals underestimate the breadth of their transferable skills because these abilities feel so natural that they do not recognize them as distinct competencies.\n"
"\n"
"Start with a comprehensive job audit. Review every position you have held and list every task, responsibility, and achievement. Do not filter based on what you think is relevant to your target career; write down everything. Once you have a complete list, categorize each item by the underlying skill it represents. \"Created monthly sales reports\" becomes \"data analysis and reporting.\" \"Mediated disputes between team members\" becomes \"conflict resolution and interpersonal communication.\"\n"
"\n"
"Ask colleagues, mentors, and friends what they see as your strongest professional abilities. Others often recognize strengths that you take for granted. A manager might tell you that your greatest asset is your ability to simplify complex information for diverse audiences, a skill you never consciously developed but one that is highly valued in fields like technical writing, user experience design, and product management.\n"
"\n"
"Use job descriptions in your target field as a reverse-engineering tool. Read through 15 to 20 postings for roles you are interested in and identify the recurring skills they mention. Then map each of those skills back to your own experience. You will likely find that you already possess many of the requested competencies; you simply have not been framing them in the right language.\n"
"\n"
"Consider taking a formal skills assessment or working with a career coach. Tools like the CliftonStrengths assessment, the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator, or the DISC assessment can provide structured insights into your natural abilities and help you articulate them more effectively on your resume."

