#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"Job search burnout is real and can significantly undermine your effectiveness. The combination of rejection, uncertainty, and repetitive effort creates a psychological burden that erodes motivation over time. Building burnout prevention into your plan from the start is far more effective than trying to recover once burnout hits.\n"
"\n"
"Set boundaries around your search time. Even if you are unemployed and searching full-time, working on your search for more than six hours a day produces diminishing returns and accelerates burnout. After your dedicated search hours, give yourself permission to step away completely. Constant rumination about the search is counterproductive and depletes the mental energy you need for interviews.\n"
"\n"
"Celebrate small wins to maintain motivation. Submitting a particularly strong application, getting a positive response from a networking contact, securing an informational interview, or learning a new skill are all achievements worth acknowledging. Create a running list of wins, no matter how small, that you can review on difficult days when progress feels invisible.\n"
"\n"
"Build accountability into your search through a job search partner, career coach, or support group. Regular check-ins with someone who understands the process provide motivation, perspective, and emotional support. Many cities and online communities have job search support groups where members share leads, practice interviews, and encourage each other through the process.\n"
"\n"
"Remember that rejection is information, not a reflection of your worth. Every application that does not result in an interview teaches you something about your targeting or materials. Every interview that does not result in an offer improves your interviewing skills. The job search process is iterative, and each experience, including the unsuccessful ones, brings you closer to the right opportunity."
msgstr ""
"Job search burnout is real and can significantly undermine your effectiveness. The combination of rejection, uncertainty, and repetitive effort creates a psychological burden that erodes motivation over time. Building burnout prevention into your plan from the start is far more effective than trying to recover once burnout hits.\n"
"\n"
"Set boundaries around your search time. Even if you are unemployed and searching full-time, working on your search for more than six hours a day produces diminishing returns and accelerates burnout. After your dedicated search hours, give yourself permission to step away completely. Constant rumination about the search is counterproductive and depletes the mental energy you need for interviews.\n"
"\n"
"Celebrate small wins to maintain motivation. Submitting a particularly strong application, getting a positive response from a networking contact, securing an informational interview, or learning a new skill are all achievements worth acknowledging. Create a running list of wins, no matter how small, that you can review on difficult days when progress feels invisible.\n"
"\n"
"Build accountability into your search through a job search partner, career coach, or support group. Regular check-ins with someone who understands the process provide motivation, perspective, and emotional support. Many cities and online communities have job search support groups where members share leads, practice interviews, and encourage each other through the process.\n"
"\n"
"Remember that rejection is information, not a reflection of your worth. Every application that does not result in an interview teaches you something about your targeting or materials. Every interview that does not result in an offer improves your interviewing skills. The job search process is iterative, and each experience, including the unsuccessful ones, brings you closer to the right opportunity."

