#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"Length and language are two areas where many cover letters fail. Writing too much and relying on tired phrases are both symptoms of the same underlying problem: not thinking strategically enough about what to include and how to say it.\n"
"\n"
"A cover letter that exceeds one page is almost never read in full. Hiring managers view excessive length as evidence that you cannot communicate concisely -- a red flag for any role that involves written communication, stakeholder management, or client interaction. The ideal cover letter is 250 to 400 words. If yours is longer, it needs editing, not more space. Challenge yourself to cut 20% of the content and notice how much stronger the remaining text becomes.\n"
"\n"
"Cliches are the empty calories of cover letter writing. Phrases like \"team player,\" \"go-getter,\" \"think outside the box,\" \"passionate and driven,\" and \"detail-oriented\" are so overused that they have lost all meaning. When a hiring manager reads \"I am a detail-oriented team player,\" they learn absolutely nothing about you because every other candidate uses the same language.\n"
"\n"
"Replace cliches with specific evidence. Instead of \"I am a team player,\" write \"I coordinated a cross-functional team of designers, engineers, and marketers to launch our mobile app two weeks ahead of schedule.\" Instead of \"I am detail-oriented,\" write \"I implemented a quality assurance checklist that reduced our document error rate by 78%.\" Specificity is the antidote to cliche.\n"
"\n"
"The same principle applies to filler phrases that pad your word count without adding value. \"I believe that,\" \"I feel that,\" \"As you can see,\" and \"It goes without saying that\" can almost always be deleted entirely without losing any meaning. Audit every sentence and ask: \"Does this tell the reader something specific about me that they could not learn from any other candidate's letter?\" If not, cut it."
msgstr ""
"Length and language are two areas where many cover letters fail. Writing too much and relying on tired phrases are both symptoms of the same underlying problem: not thinking strategically enough about what to include and how to say it.\n"
"\n"
"A cover letter that exceeds one page is almost never read in full. Hiring managers view excessive length as evidence that you cannot communicate concisely -- a red flag for any role that involves written communication, stakeholder management, or client interaction. The ideal cover letter is 250 to 400 words. If yours is longer, it needs editing, not more space. Challenge yourself to cut 20% of the content and notice how much stronger the remaining text becomes.\n"
"\n"
"Cliches are the empty calories of cover letter writing. Phrases like \"team player,\" \"go-getter,\" \"think outside the box,\" \"passionate and driven,\" and \"detail-oriented\" are so overused that they have lost all meaning. When a hiring manager reads \"I am a detail-oriented team player,\" they learn absolutely nothing about you because every other candidate uses the same language.\n"
"\n"
"Replace cliches with specific evidence. Instead of \"I am a team player,\" write \"I coordinated a cross-functional team of designers, engineers, and marketers to launch our mobile app two weeks ahead of schedule.\" Instead of \"I am detail-oriented,\" write \"I implemented a quality assurance checklist that reduced our document error rate by 78%.\" Specificity is the antidote to cliche.\n"
"\n"
"The same principle applies to filler phrases that pad your word count without adding value. \"I believe that,\" \"I feel that,\" \"As you can see,\" and \"It goes without saying that\" can almost always be deleted entirely without losing any meaning. Audit every sentence and ask: \"Does this tell the reader something specific about me that they could not learn from any other candidate's letter?\" If not, cut it."

