#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"Once you have identified your transferable skills, the challenge is presenting them on your resume in a way that resonates with hiring managers in your target industry. The key is to use the language and context of the new field rather than the old one.\n"
"\n"
"Create a dedicated skills section near the top of your resume that groups your transferable skills into categories relevant to your target role. For example, if you are transitioning into digital marketing, you might organize your skills under headings like \"Data Analysis and Reporting,\" \"Content Strategy and Communication,\" and \"Project Management and Campaign Execution.\" This immediately frames your abilities in terms the hiring manager understands.\n"
"\n"
"In your experience section, rewrite each bullet point to emphasize the transferable skill rather than the industry-specific context. Instead of \"Managed a team of 12 nurses across three hospital departments,\" write \"Led a cross-functional team of 12 professionals, coordinating schedules, resources, and deliverables across three operational units to achieve a 15 percent improvement in service delivery metrics.\" The underlying achievement is the same, but the language is industry-neutral.\n"
"\n"
"Use the STAR method (Situation, Task, Action, Result) when crafting bullet points to ensure each one tells a complete story. This structure naturally highlights your transferable skills by showing how you applied them in real situations and what outcomes you achieved. Hiring managers want evidence, not just claims.\n"
"\n"
"Include relevant keywords from your target industry throughout your resume. Applicant tracking systems scan for specific terms, and if your resume uses language from your previous industry instead, it may never reach a human reader. Study the vocabulary of your target field and weave it naturally into your skill descriptions and achievement statements."
