#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"One of the biggest challenges of using a creative resume format is ensuring it can pass through applicant tracking systems without losing critical information. ATS software is designed to parse text from structured documents, and many creative design elements can interfere with this process. Understanding how to balance visual appeal with technical compatibility is essential for any job seeker using a creative format.\n"
"\n"
"Text-based content is the foundation of ATS compatibility. All of your important information, including your name, contact details, job titles, company names, dates, skills, and achievements, must be actual text rather than embedded in images or graphics. ATS software cannot read text within image files, which means that a beautifully designed header that renders your name as an image will result in the system being unable to identify you as a candidate.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid using text boxes, tables, headers, and footers to position content. While these formatting tools can create visually appealing layouts, many ATS systems cannot extract text from these elements. Instead, use standard formatting with clear section headings that match common ATS conventions, such as \"Work Experience,\" \"Education,\" and \"Skills.\" You can still apply creative styling to these headings while keeping the underlying structure ATS-friendly.\n"
"\n"
"Columns can be problematic for some ATS systems, particularly older ones. If you use a multi-column layout, test it by copying and pasting the text from your resume into a plain text editor. If the text flows in the correct reading order, your columns are likely ATS-compatible. If the text from different columns becomes interleaved or jumbled, the ATS will have trouble parsing your information correctly.\n"
"\n"
"Consider maintaining two versions of your resume: a creative version for direct submissions, portfolio presentations, networking events, and personal websites, and a simplified ATS-friendly version for online job applications. The ATS version should contain the same content but with standard formatting, minimal visual embellishment, and a straightforward chronological or combination structure. This dual approach lets you enjoy the benefits of creative design without risking ATS rejection.\n"
"\n"
"File format matters as well. Submit your creative resume as a PDF when the application system accepts it, as this preserves your visual formatting. However, some ATS systems parse Word documents more reliably than PDFs. When in doubt, follow the file format instructions in the job posting. If no format is specified, a PDF is generally the safest choice for preserving design integrity."
