#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"Returning to work after a significant break can be emotionally challenging. Imposter syndrome is common among returning professionals, but remember that your skills and experience have genuine value.\n"
"\n"
"Start your job search before you feel completely ready. Waiting until you feel perfectly prepared is a common trap that can extend your time out of the workforce unnecessarily. Apply for roles that interest you even if you do not meet every single qualification listed. Job descriptions often represent an employer's wish list, and candidates who meet 60 to 70 percent of the requirements are frequently considered.\n"
"\n"
"Practice your professional communication skills by conducting informational interviews with people in your target field. These conversations help you refine your narrative about your career gap, understand current industry needs, and build relationships that may lead to job opportunities. They also help you rebuild your professional confidence in a low-pressure setting.\n"
"\n"
"Update your LinkedIn profile to match your resume and actively engage with professional content. Share articles, comment thoughtfully on industry posts, and participate in relevant groups. A strong online presence demonstrates that you are engaged and current, even before you land your next role.\n"
"\n"
"Consider working with a career coach who specializes in return-to-work transitions. A good coach can help you identify your strengths, develop your job search strategy, practice interviewing, and navigate the emotional aspects of reentering the workforce. Many organizations also offer free or subsidized career support programs for returning professionals."
msgstr ""
"Returning to work after a significant break can be emotionally challenging. Imposter syndrome is common among returning professionals, but remember that your skills and experience have genuine value.\n"
"\n"
"Start your job search before you feel completely ready. Waiting until you feel perfectly prepared is a common trap that can extend your time out of the workforce unnecessarily. Apply for roles that interest you even if you do not meet every single qualification listed. Job descriptions often represent an employer's wish list, and candidates who meet 60 to 70 percent of the requirements are frequently considered.\n"
"\n"
"Practice your professional communication skills by conducting informational interviews with people in your target field. These conversations help you refine your narrative about your career gap, understand current industry needs, and build relationships that may lead to job opportunities. They also help you rebuild your professional confidence in a low-pressure setting.\n"
"\n"
"Update your LinkedIn profile to match your resume and actively engage with professional content. Share articles, comment thoughtfully on industry posts, and participate in relevant groups. A strong online presence demonstrates that you are engaged and current, even before you land your next role.\n"
"\n"
"Consider working with a career coach who specializes in return-to-work transitions. A good coach can help you identify your strengths, develop your job search strategy, practice interviewing, and navigate the emotional aspects of reentering the workforce. Many organizations also offer free or subsidized career support programs for returning professionals."

