#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"Several persistent myths surround the functional resume format, and understanding the truth behind them is essential for making an informed decision about your resume strategy. One common myth is that functional resumes are universally rejected by employers. While it is true that some recruiters prefer chronological formats, a well-crafted functional resume can still be effective, particularly in industries that value skills and creativity over rigid career timelines. Creative fields, startups, and non-profit organizations may be more receptive to non-traditional formats.\n"
"\n"
"Another myth is that functional resumes are only for people who are trying to hide something. While the format does de-emphasize your work timeline, using it does not automatically signal dishonesty. Many legitimate scenarios call for a skills-first approach, including career transitions, military-to-civilian moves, and returns from extended education. The key is to be transparent in your professional summary about your situation and to include a brief but honest work history section.\n"
"\n"
"Some job seekers believe that a functional resume means they do not need to include any work history at all. This is a misconception that can seriously hurt your chances. Omitting your work history entirely will almost certainly raise red flags. Even in a functional format, you should include a concise employment section with job titles, company names, and dates. The difference is that this section takes a supporting role rather than being the centerpiece of your resume.\n"
"\n"
"There is also a myth that functional resumes perform well with applicant tracking systems because they can be loaded with keywords. While you can certainly include relevant keywords in your skills sections, ATS software relies on parsing structured data that includes job titles matched with dates and companies. A functional resume disrupts this structure, which can lead to parsing errors and lower match scores regardless of how many keywords you include.\n"
"\n"
"Finally, some candidates believe that a functional resume is always the best choice for career changers. While it can be effective, many career counselors now recommend the combination format instead. The combination format allows you to lead with your transferable skills while still providing the chronological work history that recruiters expect. This hybrid approach gives you the best of both worlds and avoids the skepticism that sometimes accompanies purely functional resumes."
msgstr ""
