#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"Technology professionals have access to some of the most developed niche job boards. GitHub Jobs, Stack Overflow Jobs, Hacker News Who is Hiring threads, and AngelList (now Wellfound) for startups each attract a distinct subset of employers and roles. Remote-specific tech boards like We Work Remotely, Remote.co, and FlexJobs have grown significantly as distributed work has become mainstream.\n"
"\n"
"Creative and media professionals benefit from platforms like Behance Jobs, Dribbble, MediaBistro, and Contently. These platforms allow you to showcase your portfolio alongside your profile, giving employers a direct look at your work quality. For design and UX roles specifically, platforms where visual work is front and center tend to produce higher quality matches than general job boards.\n"
"\n"
"Healthcare, education, and government sectors each have specialized job boards that are often the primary posting channel for employers in those fields. HigherEdJobs for academia, USAJobs for federal government, Health eCareers for healthcare, and SchoolSpring for K-12 education are essential platforms that many job seekers outside these sectors may not know about.\n"
"\n"
"Executive and senior-level positions are increasingly found on platforms like Ladders, ExecuNet, and BlueSteps. These platforms cater to positions above a certain salary threshold and provide access to senior recruiters and executive search firms. For mid-to-senior roles, industry-specific recruiter networks and retained search firms often fill positions that never appear on public job boards at all.\n"
"\n"
"Diversity-focused job boards like DiversityJobs, PowerToFly, Jopwell, and Out in Tech connect underrepresented professionals with employers committed to inclusive hiring. These platforms are valuable not only for the job listings but also for the employer research they provide, helping candidates identify companies with genuine commitments to diversity rather than surface-level initiatives."
msgstr ""
"Technology professionals have access to some of the most developed niche job boards. GitHub Jobs, Stack Overflow Jobs, Hacker News Who is Hiring threads, and AngelList (now Wellfound) for startups each attract a distinct subset of employers and roles. Remote-specific tech boards like We Work Remotely, Remote.co, and FlexJobs have grown significantly as distributed work has become mainstream.\n"
"\n"
"Creative and media professionals benefit from platforms like Behance Jobs, Dribbble, MediaBistro, and Contently. These platforms allow you to showcase your portfolio alongside your profile, giving employers a direct look at your work quality. For design and UX roles specifically, platforms where visual work is front and center tend to produce higher quality matches than general job boards.\n"
"\n"
"Healthcare, education, and government sectors each have specialized job boards that are often the primary posting channel for employers in those fields. HigherEdJobs for academia, USAJobs for federal government, Health eCareers for healthcare, and SchoolSpring for K-12 education are essential platforms that many job seekers outside these sectors may not know about.\n"
"\n"
"Executive and senior-level positions are increasingly found on platforms like Ladders, ExecuNet, and BlueSteps. These platforms cater to positions above a certain salary threshold and provide access to senior recruiters and executive search firms. For mid-to-senior roles, industry-specific recruiter networks and retained search firms often fill positions that never appear on public job boards at all.\n"
"\n"
"Diversity-focused job boards like DiversityJobs, PowerToFly, Jopwell, and Out in Tech connect underrepresented professionals with employers committed to inclusive hiring. These platforms are valuable not only for the job listings but also for the employer research they provide, helping candidates identify companies with genuine commitments to diversity rather than surface-level initiatives."

