#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"The culmination of your company research is turning insights into interview-ready talking points that demonstrate genuine understanding and enthusiasm. Create a one-page company research brief before each interview that summarizes the company's mission, recent achievements, challenges, competitive position, and the specific team's focus areas.\n"
"\n"
"Reference your research naturally during interviews rather than forcing rehearsed facts into conversation. When asked \"Why do you want to work here?\" a response that references specific projects, values, or strategic initiatives you discovered through research is exponentially more compelling than generic statements about the company being a great place to work.\n"
"\n"
"Prepare thoughtful questions based on your research. Instead of asking \"What does the company do?\" which suggests zero preparation, ask \"I noticed the company recently expanded into the European market. How has that affected the team's priorities?\" or \"I read that the CEO spoke about increasing investment in AI capabilities. How does that translate to the engineering roadmap for this team?\"\n"
"\n"
"Use your research to identify potential concerns and address them proactively. If the company recently had layoffs, you might ask thoughtfully about current team stability and growth plans. If Glassdoor reviews mention work-life balance challenges, explore the topic by asking about typical work hours and how the team manages peak periods. Addressing potential red flags directly shows maturity and thoroughness.\n"
"\n"
"After the interview, use your research to write a personalized thank-you note that reinforces specific connections between your conversation and the company's needs. Reference a specific topic from the interview, connect it to something you learned in your research, and reiterate how your experience addresses a real need you identified. This level of personalization sets you apart from candidates who send generic follow-ups."
