#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"The effectiveness of a functional resume hinges on how well you organize and present your skills. Begin by carefully analyzing the job descriptions for positions you are targeting. Identify the three to five most important skill areas or competencies that employers are seeking. These will become the headings for your skill categories. Common categories include project management, technical expertise, leadership, communication, data analysis, customer relations, and strategic planning.\n"
"\n"
"Under each skill category, list three to five specific accomplishments or examples that demonstrate your proficiency. These should be drawn from any relevant experience, including formal employment, freelance work, volunteer activities, academic projects, or personal initiatives. The key is to treat each bullet point as evidence of your capability, not just a description of a task you performed.\n"
"\n"
"When writing your skill bullets, follow the same principles of strong resume writing that apply to any format. Use action verbs, quantify results when possible, and focus on outcomes rather than duties. For example, under a \"Project Management\" heading, you might write \"coordinated cross-functional team of 8 members to deliver a product launch 2 weeks ahead of schedule, resulting in a 15% increase in first-quarter revenue.\"\n"
"\n"
"Be strategic about the order in which you present your skill categories. Place the most relevant category first, as this is what the reader will see immediately. If the job emphasizes leadership and you have strong leadership examples, make that your first category. If it emphasizes technical skills, lead with those instead.\n"
"\n"
"Include a brief work history section below your skills section. Even though the functional format de-emphasizes chronological history, omitting it entirely can raise red flags with recruiters. List your positions with job title, company name, and dates of employment. You do not need to include bullet points or detailed descriptions for each role since your skills section already covers your accomplishments.\n"
"\n"
"Finally, ensure that your skills section tells a coherent story. Each category should build upon the last, creating a comprehensive picture of your professional identity. Avoid listing skills that are too broad or too vague, such as \"good communication\" or \"team player.\" Instead, provide specific, evidence-backed demonstrations of those abilities that give the reader confidence in your qualifications."
