#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"The experience section is where career changers face their greatest challenge. Every bullet point must be carefully crafted to emphasize the aspects of your previous roles that align with your target career.\n"
"\n"
"Start by conducting a thorough audit of your past responsibilities and achievements. For each item, ask yourself: \"How does this relate to the job I want?\" You will likely find that many of your accomplishments have direct parallels in your target industry. A teacher who managed a classroom of 30 students while meeting individualized education goals has project management skills. A sales representative who analyzed market trends and customer behavior has data analysis capabilities.\n"
"\n"
"Use action verbs that are common in your target industry. If you are transitioning into technology, words like \"implemented,\" \"optimized,\" \"analyzed,\" and \"automated\" carry more weight than \"taught,\" \"counseled,\" or \"supervised,\" even if the underlying skills are the same. This linguistic alignment helps hiring managers mentally place you in the new role.\n"
"\n"
"Quantify your achievements wherever possible. Numbers transcend industry boundaries. Whether you increased revenue by 25 percent, reduced processing time by 40 percent, or managed a budget of half a million dollars, these metrics demonstrate impact in a universal language that every hiring manager understands.\n"
"\n"
"Remove or minimize details that anchor you too firmly in your previous industry. If you spent ten years in healthcare administration and are transitioning to tech project management, you do not need to list every healthcare-specific certification or procedure you are familiar with. Keep the focus on the transferable elements: leadership, process improvement, stakeholder management, and data-driven decision making."
