#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"The final two critical mistakes relate to the end of your letter and the beginning of the application process, respectively. Both are easy to fix once you are aware of them, but failing to address them can render even an otherwise excellent cover letter ineffective.\n"
"\n"
"Ending your cover letter without a call to action is like building a compelling sales presentation and then forgetting to ask for the sale. Many candidates close with a passive \"Thank you for your consideration\" and stop, leaving the next steps entirely in the hiring manager's hands. A strong call to action gently moves the process forward: \"I would welcome the opportunity to discuss how my experience can contribute to your team's goals and am available for a conversation at your earliest convenience.\" This signals confidence and makes it easy for the hiring manager to take the next step.\n"
"\n"
"Failing to follow application instructions is perhaps the most avoidable mistake on this list, yet it disqualifies more candidates than you might expect. When a job posting asks for specific information in your cover letter -- such as salary requirements, availability date, references, or answers to screening questions -- you must include that information. Ignoring these instructions suggests that you either did not read the posting carefully or chose to disregard it, neither of which reflects well on you.\n"
"\n"
"Similarly, if the posting specifies the file format (PDF versus Word), the subject line for email submissions, or the method of delivery (portal versus email), follow those instructions exactly. Some employers use specific instructions as a screening test to filter out candidates who do not pay attention to details. Compliance with instructions costs you nothing and eliminates an easy reason for rejection.\n"
"\n"
"Read the job posting at least twice before finalizing your application: once for the role requirements that inform your letter's content, and once for the application logistics that determine how you submit it. This simple habit prevents one of the most frustrating outcomes in the job search -- being eliminated not for lack of qualifications, but for lack of attention to detail."
