#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"The first paragraph of your cover letter is the most important section of your entire application. Hiring managers typically make a snap judgment within the first few sentences about whether your letter is worth reading in full. A compelling opening hooks the reader immediately, while a bland or generic introduction causes them to lose interest and move on to the next candidate's application.\n"
"\n"
"Think of your opening paragraph as the headline of a newspaper article. Just as a great headline draws readers into the story, a strong cover letter opening draws the hiring manager into your professional narrative. You have roughly 5 to 10 seconds to convince the reader that your letter contains something worth their time. This is not hyperbole -- with hundreds of applications to review, hiring managers develop a rapid-fire filtering process that eliminates generic letters almost instantly.\n"
"\n"
"The opening paragraph should accomplish three things simultaneously: identify the role you are applying for, establish your most compelling qualification or connection to the company, and create enough intrigue that the reader feels compelled to continue. This is a tall order for just two or three sentences, which is precisely why crafting the perfect opening requires more time and thought than any other part of the letter.\n"
"\n"
"Common advice to \"just be yourself\" in your opening is well-intentioned but incomplete. You need to be the most strategic, articulate version of yourself. The opening paragraph is where you deploy your strongest weapon -- whether that is a remarkable achievement, a personal connection to the company's mission, or a unique perspective that no other candidate can offer."
