#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"The format of your cover letter is as important as its content. A well-formatted cover letter communicates professionalism, attention to detail, and respect for the reader's time before they even begin reading your words. Conversely, a poorly formatted letter -- with inconsistent spacing, walls of text, or unconventional layouts -- can create a negative first impression that undermines even the strongest qualifications.\n"
"\n"
"The standard professional cover letter follows a business letter format that has evolved for the digital age. While traditional business letters required strict formatting rules for physical mail, modern cover letters are typically submitted as PDF attachments or pasted into online application systems. Regardless of the submission method, the fundamental structure remains consistent: a header with contact information, a greeting, body paragraphs, and a professional closing.\n"
"\n"
"Understanding this format is not about rigidly following outdated conventions. It is about leveraging a structure that hiring managers expect and can process quickly. When your cover letter follows the expected format, the reader can focus on your message rather than being distracted by an unusual layout. This is especially important when your letter passes through applicant tracking systems, which may struggle to parse non-standard formatting.\n"
"\n"
"The key principle underlying all cover letter formatting decisions is readability. Every choice you make about margins, fonts, spacing, and structure should serve the goal of making your content as easy to read and absorb as possible. A hiring manager reviewing dozens or hundreds of applications will naturally gravitate toward letters that are clean, organized, and visually inviting."
