#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"The format you choose for your career change resume can make or break your application. The three main formats, chronological, functional, and combination, each have distinct advantages and disadvantages for career changers.\n"
"\n"
"A functional resume organizes your experience by skill category rather than by employer and date. This format allows you to group transferable skills together, making it easier for hiring managers to see your relevant qualifications. However, many recruiters are suspicious of functional resumes because they can obscure employment gaps or a lack of direct experience.\n"
"\n"
"The combination format, also called a hybrid resume, is generally the best choice for career changers. It starts with a strong skills section or professional summary that highlights your transferable qualifications, followed by a brief chronological work history. This gives you the best of both worlds: the ability to lead with relevance while still providing the employment timeline that recruiters expect.\n"
"\n"
"Regardless of format, your resume should be tailored to each specific job posting. Use the job description as a blueprint, identifying the key skills and qualifications mentioned, and mirror that language in your resume. Applicant tracking systems (ATS) are programmed to look for specific keywords, so aligning your language with the job description is essential for getting past the initial automated screening.\n"
"\n"
"Consider adding a career summary statement at the top of your resume that explicitly addresses your transition. A statement like \"Marketing professional with 8 years of data-driven campaign management transitioning to product management\" immediately tells the reader who you are, what you bring, and where you are headed."
