#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"The hidden job market refers to the estimated 60 to 80 percent of positions that are filled without ever being publicly advertised. These roles are filled through internal promotions, employee referrals, recruiter sourcing, and direct outreach from hiring managers to professionals they have identified through their networks. If you are only applying to posted positions, you are competing for a fraction of available opportunities.\n"
"\n"
"Companies fill positions without posting them for several practical reasons. Posting a job publicly attracts hundreds of applications, creating a significant screening burden for hiring teams. Internal referrals and network hires tend to have higher retention rates and faster ramp-up times, making them the preferred hiring channel for many organizations. Additionally, some positions are confidential replacements or newly created roles that the company prefers not to publicize.\n"
"\n"
"Accessing the hidden job market requires a fundamentally different approach than responding to job postings. Instead of being reactive, applying to positions that employers have already defined and posted, you become proactive, building relationships and demonstrating value so that opportunities flow to you. This shift from application-driven to relationship-driven job searching is the single most impactful change most professionals can make.\n"
"\n"
"The hidden job market advantage is particularly significant for senior and specialized roles, where the pool of qualified candidates is smaller and the consequences of a bad hire are larger. Companies filling these positions prefer to work with known quantities, whether through their own network, trusted referrals, or executive recruiters, rather than sorting through a public applicant pool."
