#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"The ideal cover letter is between 250 and 400 words, which typically translates to three or four well-developed paragraphs that fit comfortably on a single page. This length gives you enough space to make a compelling case without testing the reader's patience. Research consistently shows that hiring managers prefer concise cover letters, with most reporting that one page is the ideal length.\n"
"\n"
"Structure your letter with a clear opening paragraph (2-3 sentences), one or two body paragraphs (3-5 sentences each), and a closing paragraph (2-3 sentences). The opening should capture attention and state your purpose. Body paragraphs should present your strongest qualifications with specific evidence. The closing should reiterate your value and include a call to action.\n"
"\n"
"Each paragraph should focus on a single main idea. Your opening paragraph introduces you and establishes interest. Your first body paragraph might focus on your most relevant professional achievement. Your second body paragraph could highlight additional skills or cultural fit. Your closing wraps everything up with enthusiasm and a clear next step. This focused approach prevents the common problem of paragraphs that try to cover too much ground and end up saying nothing memorable.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid the temptation to tell your entire career story. A cover letter is not a comprehensive autobiography -- it is a carefully curated highlight reel that makes the reader want to learn more by reviewing your resume and inviting you for an interview. Select only the most relevant and impressive elements of your background, and save the rest for the conversation.\n"
"\n"
"If you are struggling to stay within the one-page limit, prioritize ruthlessly. Every sentence should either demonstrate a relevant qualification, show knowledge of the company, or move the reader closer to inviting you for an interview. Sentences that do not accomplish at least one of these goals should be cut, no matter how well-written they are."
