#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"The informational interview is one of the most powerful tools for accessing the hidden job market, yet it is dramatically underutilized. An informational interview is a 20 to 30 minute conversation with a professional in your target field, company, or role, designed to learn about their experience and gather insights that inform your job search. It is explicitly not a job interview, and that distinction is critical.\n"
"\n"
"Request informational interviews by being clear about your intentions and respectful of the person's time. A strong outreach message explains who you are, why you are reaching out to this person specifically, what you hope to learn, and that you are requesting a brief conversation rather than a job. For example: \"I am transitioning into data science from software engineering and would greatly appreciate 20 minutes of your time to learn about your career path and any advice you would offer someone making this transition.\"\n"
"\n"
"Prepare thoughtful questions that demonstrate research and genuine curiosity. Ask about their career path, what they enjoy about their role, what challenges the industry faces, what skills are most valuable, and what advice they would give someone entering the field. Avoid asking directly for a job or referral during the informational interview itself, as this violates the implicit agreement and damages trust.\n"
"\n"
"The hidden job market access happens through what occurs after the informational interview. Follow up with a genuine thank-you note referencing specific insights from the conversation. Stay in touch periodically with relevant articles or updates on your career progress. When a position opens on their team or in their network, you will be the person they think of because you have already demonstrated initiative, professionalism, and genuine interest.\n"
"\n"
"Many informational interviews lead to introductions without you having to ask. When someone meets a thoughtful, prepared professional who is clearly a strong candidate, the natural impulse is to say \"You should talk to my colleague at Company X\" or \"We actually have a role opening up that might interest you.\" By approaching the conversation without a transactional agenda, you often achieve better outcomes than you would by asking directly."
