#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"The number one concern employers have when considering freelance candidates for full-time roles is whether they will stay. Your resume needs to proactively address this concern without being defensive.\n"
"\n"
"Highlight long-term client relationships. If you worked with any clients for an extended period (six months or more), emphasize the duration of these engagements. Long-term client relationships demonstrate that you can commit to ongoing work and build lasting professional partnerships. \"Served as primary design consultant for a Fortune 500 financial services firm for 18 months\" sends a clear message about your ability to maintain long-term commitments.\n"
"\n"
"Show evidence of teamwork and collaboration. One of the perceived downsides of freelancers is that they are lone wolves who cannot work within team structures. Counter this by describing projects where you collaborated with other team members, worked within established processes, or integrated into existing organizational workflows. Phrases like \"collaborated with cross-functional teams,\" \"integrated into the client's agile development workflow,\" and \"coordinated with internal stakeholders\" demonstrate your ability to work as part of a larger organization.\n"
"\n"
"Include any full-time or long-term contract positions in your work history, even if they were interspersed with freelance periods. These entries show that you have experience working within organizational structures and can thrive in a traditional employment setting.\n"
"\n"
"In your professional summary, address your motivation for transitioning to full-time work. A brief statement like \"seeking to bring entrepreneurial drive and diverse industry experience to a dedicated full-time role\" frames your transition positively. Avoid language that suggests freelancing was not working out or that you need the stability of full-time employment. Instead, position the transition as a proactive choice driven by professional goals."
