#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"The quality of a company's leadership team, and particularly your direct management chain, will have a more significant impact on your daily experience than almost any other factor. Research the CEO, your potential department leader, and if possible, your direct manager before investing time in the application process.\n"
"\n"
"LinkedIn is the primary tool for leadership research. Review the backgrounds of executives and managers for relevant experience, tenure patterns, and career trajectories. A leadership team with deep industry experience and long tenures suggests stability and domain expertise. High leadership turnover or a team composed entirely of recent hires may indicate organizational instability.\n"
"\n"
"Seek out interviews, conference talks, podcast appearances, and blog posts by company leaders. These public communications reveal leadership style, strategic thinking, and values in ways that a LinkedIn profile cannot. A CEO who speaks thoughtfully about employee development and long-term strategy projects a very different culture than one focused exclusively on aggressive growth metrics.\n"
"\n"
"Glassdoor CEO approval ratings and leadership reviews provide employee perspectives on management quality. While these should be taken as one data point among many, a CEO approval rating below 60 percent is a warning sign that warrants further investigation. Reviews that consistently mention issues with specific department leaders are particularly relevant if you would be reporting to that team.\n"
"\n"
"If you can identify your potential direct manager, research their background thoroughly. The relationship with your direct manager is the single strongest predictor of job satisfaction according to decades of Gallup research. Look for signals of management style, team tenure under their leadership, and whether team members have been promoted during their time on the team."
