#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"The sign-off is the final visual element of your cover letter, and choosing the right one matters more than many candidates realize. Your sign-off should match the tone of your letter and the culture of the organization while maintaining professionalism.\n"
"\n"
"The safest and most universally appropriate sign-offs are \"Sincerely,\" \"Best regards,\" and \"Kind regards.\" These work for any industry, any level of formality, and any type of role. If your letter has maintained a slightly more conversational tone, \"Best,\" or \"Warm regards,\" are acceptable alternatives that feel approachable without sacrificing professionalism.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid overly casual sign-offs like \"Cheers,\" \"Thanks,\" or \"Talk soon\" unless you have a pre-existing relationship with the recipient or the company culture is extremely informal (and you are certain of this based on research, not assumption). On the other end of the spectrum, avoid antiquated formal sign-offs like \"Respectfully yours,\" \"Your humble servant,\" or \"I remain, your obedient applicant\" which feel comically outdated.\n"
"\n"
"After your sign-off, include your full name. If submitting a PDF or physical letter, consider adding a digital signature above your typed name for a polished touch. Below your name, you may include your phone number and email address again for convenience, especially if submitting through a portal where your header information might be separated from the letter body.\n"
"\n"
"Ensure there is appropriate spacing between your closing paragraph and your sign-off (one blank line) and between your sign-off and your name. If your letter will be printed, leave enough space (three to four lines) between the sign-off and your typed name for a physical signature. These formatting details may seem minor, but they contribute to the overall impression of professionalism and care."
msgstr ""
