#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"The structure of your resume should be designed to lead with your most marketable qualities while providing clear context for your military background.\n"
"\n"
"Open with a strong professional summary that positions you as a civilian professional. State your years of experience, your key competencies in civilian terms, and your target role or industry. For example: \"Operations and logistics leader with 10 years of experience managing teams of up to 50 personnel, overseeing multimillion-dollar equipment inventories, and executing complex projects in high-pressure environments. Seeking a supply chain management role in the manufacturing sector.\"\n"
"\n"
"Create a skills section that highlights your most transferable competencies. Common military-to-civilian transferable skills include leadership and team management, strategic planning and execution, risk assessment and mitigation, logistics and supply chain management, training and personnel development, budget management, communication and briefing, crisis management, and technology proficiency.\n"
"\n"
"In your experience section, list each military position with a translated job title followed by your actual rank and unit in parentheses if you choose. This approach gives civilian readers an immediate understanding of your role while preserving the specifics of your service for those who understand military structure.\n"
"\n"
"Quantify everything you can. Military experience often involves impressive numbers: personnel managed, budgets controlled, equipment valued, operations conducted, and improvements achieved. These metrics speak a universal language. \"Managed logistics operations for a $12 million equipment inventory\" is meaningful to any hiring manager, regardless of whether they understand the military context."
