#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"The veteran community has developed extensive resources to support military-to-civilian career transitions, and taking advantage of these resources can significantly improve your job search outcomes.\n"
"\n"
"Many large employers have dedicated veteran hiring programs and actively seek candidates with military backgrounds. Companies like Amazon, Microsoft, JPMorgan Chase, and Deloitte have formal programs that include mentorship, accelerated onboarding, and veteran-specific career development tracks. Research which companies in your target industry have veteran-friendly hiring practices and prioritize those in your job search.\n"
"\n"
"Government resources like the Department of Veterans Affairs Vocational Rehabilitation and Employment program, the Transition Assistance Program (TAP), and the Veterans Employment and Training Service (VETS) offer free career counseling, resume review, and job placement assistance. These programs understand the unique challenges of military-to-civilian transition and can provide targeted support.\n"
"\n"
"Veteran networking organizations such as American Corporate Partners, Veterati, and the Institute for Veterans and Military Families connect transitioning service members with civilian mentors and professional networks. A mentor who has successfully navigated the transition themselves can provide invaluable guidance on everything from resume writing to salary negotiation.\n"
"\n"
"Professional associations in your target industry may have veteran-specific membership programs or networking events. The Project Management Institute, for example, offers reduced membership rates and specialized resources for veterans. These associations help you build industry-specific connections and stay current with trends and best practices in your target field.\n"
"\n"
"Consider having your resume reviewed by someone who specializes in military-to-civilian transitions. Many veteran service organizations offer free resume reviews, and career coaches who specialize in veteran transitions understand both the military terminology and the civilian expectations."
