#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"The way you structure your freelance experience on a resume depends on the volume and diversity of your freelance work. There are several effective approaches, and the right one depends on your specific situation.\n"
"\n"
"If your freelance work was focused in a single niche, treat it like a single job. Create one entry with a professional title (such as \"Freelance UX Designer\" or \"Independent Marketing Consultant\"), list the date range of your freelance career, and write bullet points that highlight your best projects and most impressive achievements. This approach presents a clean, easy-to-scan work history.\n"
"\n"
"If you worked with a few notable clients on long-term engagements, consider listing each major client as a separate entry within your freelance period. This works well when the client names carry recognition value or when the projects were substantial enough to warrant individual attention. Format these entries similarly to how you would list positions at different companies, with the client name serving as the employer.\n"
"\n"
"For freelancers with diverse project portfolios, a hybrid approach works best. Create an umbrella entry for your freelance career with a few high-level bullet points summarizing your overall scope and achievements, then add a \"Key Projects\" subsection that highlights three to five of your most relevant and impressive engagements with brief descriptions of each.\n"
"\n"
"Regardless of the structure you choose, always include metrics. Revenue generated, clients served, projects completed, deadlines met, and other quantifiable achievements help hiring managers evaluate your freelance work with the same rigor they would apply to traditional employment. \"Delivered 47 web development projects over 3 years with a 100 percent on-time completion rate\" is far more compelling than \"Freelance web developer.\""
