#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"The way you submit your cover letter matters just as much as how you write it. Different submission methods require different formatting considerations, and failing to optimize for the delivery medium can undermine an otherwise excellent letter.\n"
"\n"
"When submitting as an email attachment, always use PDF format unless the employer specifically requests a different file type. PDFs preserve your formatting exactly as intended, regardless of the recipient's operating system, software version, or font availability. Word documents can shift formatting, display differently on various systems, and even expose tracked changes or metadata you did not intend to share. Name your file professionally: \"FirstName_LastName_Cover_Letter.pdf\" is clear and easy to organize.\n"
"\n"
"For online application portals, you may need to paste your cover letter into a text field rather than uploading a file. In these cases, formatting will be stripped down to plain text, so ensure your letter reads well without relying on bold text, italics, or special formatting. Use blank lines between paragraphs to maintain readability and remove any special characters that might not render properly in web forms.\n"
"\n"
"Some employers request that the cover letter be included in the body of an email rather than as an attachment. In this case, keep your header minimal (just your name and the date) and let your email signature provide contact details. The same content rules apply, but be especially concise since email readers tend to scan even more quickly than document readers.\n"
"\n"
"Regardless of the submission method, always test your document before sending. Open your PDF on different devices to check formatting. Send a test email to yourself to verify that pasted text displays correctly. These small quality assurance steps take only a minute but can prevent embarrassing formatting issues that distract from your qualifications."
