#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"There are several strategies for addressing career gaps on your resume, and the right approach depends on the length of the gap, the reason for it, and your target role.\n"
"\n"
"For gaps of less than a year, you may not need to address them explicitly. Using years only (instead of months and years) in your employment dates can naturally minimize the appearance of short gaps without being dishonest. For example, listing a position as \"2019-2021\" rather than \"March 2019-January 2021\" gives you more flexibility.\n"
"\n"
"For longer gaps, consider adding a brief entry in your work history section that accounts for the time. This could be labeled \"Career Sabbatical,\" \"Family Leave,\" \"Professional Development,\" or simply the activity you pursued. Keep the description concise and focus on any skills you maintained or developed during the period.\n"
"\n"
"If you pursued education, freelance work, volunteer activities, or personal projects during your gap, create entries for these that highlight relevant skills and accomplishments. A parent who managed household finances, coordinated schedules for multiple family members, and volunteered at a school developed real organizational, financial, and leadership skills. Frame these experiences professionally.\n"
"\n"
"Your professional summary is another effective place to address the gap. A statement like \"Experienced marketing professional returning to the workforce after a two-year caregiving sabbatical, bringing refreshed perspective and up-to-date skills through recent certification in digital marketing analytics\" turns the gap into a narrative of growth rather than absence.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid leaving the gap unaddressed and hoping no one will notice. Recruiters are trained to spot gaps, and an unexplained period of absence creates uncertainty. It is always better to provide a brief, honest explanation than to leave hiring managers wondering."
