#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"Three of the most damaging cover letter mistakes are also the most easily preventable, yet they continue to plague applications across every industry. These errors are particularly costly because they signal carelessness -- the opposite of what employers want in a new hire.\n"
"\n"
"Typos and grammatical errors are the number one reason hiring managers report immediately rejecting a cover letter. A single misspelling can undo paragraphs of compelling content because it raises questions about your attention to detail and professionalism. Always proofread your letter at least twice, read it aloud to catch errors your eyes might miss, use a grammar-checking tool as a safety net, and have another person review it before submission. Never rely solely on spell-check, which cannot catch correctly spelled words used incorrectly (such as \"their\" instead of \"there\").\n"
"\n"
"Addressing your letter to the wrong company -- or worse, the wrong hiring manager -- is a catastrophic error that immediately reveals you are mass-mailing applications without checking. This mistake is surprisingly common, especially when candidates are applying to multiple positions simultaneously. Before sending every single application, triple-check that the company name, hiring manager's name, job title, and any company-specific references are correct.\n"
"\n"
"Poor formatting -- inconsistent fonts, enormous walls of text, misaligned margins, or colorful designs that look unprofessional -- creates a negative visual impression before the reader absorbs a single word. Stick to the standard business letter format with clean, consistent typography. Use white space strategically to improve readability. If your letter looks different from what a hiring manager expects, the formatting itself becomes a distraction that overshadows your content."
msgstr ""
"Three of the most damaging cover letter mistakes are also the most easily preventable, yet they continue to plague applications across every industry. These errors are particularly costly because they signal carelessness -- the opposite of what employers want in a new hire.\n"
"\n"
"Typos and grammatical errors are the number one reason hiring managers report immediately rejecting a cover letter. A single misspelling can undo paragraphs of compelling content because it raises questions about your attention to detail and professionalism. Always proofread your letter at least twice, read it aloud to catch errors your eyes might miss, use a grammar-checking tool as a safety net, and have another person review it before submission. Never rely solely on spell-check, which cannot catch correctly spelled words used incorrectly (such as \"their\" instead of \"there\").\n"
"\n"
"Addressing your letter to the wrong company -- or worse, the wrong hiring manager -- is a catastrophic error that immediately reveals you are mass-mailing applications without checking. This mistake is surprisingly common, especially when candidates are applying to multiple positions simultaneously. Before sending every single application, triple-check that the company name, hiring manager's name, job title, and any company-specific references are correct.\n"
"\n"
"Poor formatting -- inconsistent fonts, enormous walls of text, misaligned margins, or colorful designs that look unprofessional -- creates a negative visual impression before the reader absorbs a single word. Stick to the standard business letter format with clean, consistent typography. Use white space strategically to improve readability. If your letter looks different from what a hiring manager expects, the formatting itself becomes a distraction that overshadows your content."

