#: src/data/wiki/categories/salary-negotiation.ts
msgid ""
"Timing is a critical but often overlooked element of salary negotiation. The optimal time to negotiate is after you have received a formal offer but before you have accepted it. At this point, the employer has invested significant time and resources in the hiring process and has decided you are their preferred candidate. Their motivation to close the deal is at its peak.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid discussing specific salary numbers during initial interviews if possible. When asked about salary expectations early in the process, redirect with something like \"I would like to learn more about the role and responsibilities before discussing compensation. I am confident we can find a number that works for both of us.\" This preserves your negotiating leverage until you have maximum information about the role and the employer is most invested in you.\n"
"\n"
"If pressed to provide a number or range before the offer stage, give a researched range rather than a single number. Make the bottom of your range your actual target, so that even if the employer anchors on the lower end of your stated range, you end up at an acceptable number.\n"
"\n"
"For internal promotions or annual raises, timing your request matters as well. The best time is typically during performance review cycles, after completing a major project, or when you have taken on significant additional responsibilities. Avoid asking for raises during company financial difficulties, immediately after layoffs, or when your manager is dealing with other high-stress situations. Reading the organizational context is part of the negotiation strategy.\n"
"\n"
"Consider the fiscal calendar as well. Many companies set budgets annually, so a raise request in October may be more successful than one in March if the fiscal year starts in January, because the budget for the coming year is still being finalized and there is room to include your increase."
msgstr ""
"Timing is a critical but often overlooked element of salary negotiation. The optimal time to negotiate is after you have received a formal offer but before you have accepted it. At this point, the employer has invested significant time and resources in the hiring process and has decided you are their preferred candidate. Their motivation to close the deal is at its peak.\n"
"\n"
"Avoid discussing specific salary numbers during initial interviews if possible. When asked about salary expectations early in the process, redirect with something like \"I would like to learn more about the role and responsibilities before discussing compensation. I am confident we can find a number that works for both of us.\" This preserves your negotiating leverage until you have maximum information about the role and the employer is most invested in you.\n"
"\n"
"If pressed to provide a number or range before the offer stage, give a researched range rather than a single number. Make the bottom of your range your actual target, so that even if the employer anchors on the lower end of your stated range, you end up at an acceptable number.\n"
"\n"
"For internal promotions or annual raises, timing your request matters as well. The best time is typically during performance review cycles, after completing a major project, or when you have taken on significant additional responsibilities. Avoid asking for raises during company financial difficulties, immediately after layoffs, or when your manager is dealing with other high-stress situations. Reading the organizational context is part of the negotiation strategy.\n"
"\n"
"Consider the fiscal calendar as well. Many companies set budgets annually, so a raise request in October may be more successful than one in March if the fiscal year starts in January, because the budget for the coming year is still being finalized and there is room to include your increase."

#: src/data/wiki/categories/interview-preparation.ts
msgid ""
"Timing is critical in the follow-up process, and getting it right requires a balance between showing interest and respecting boundaries. The thank you email should be sent within twenty-four hours, ideally on the same day as the interview. If you interviewed in the morning, send it by the afternoon. If you had an afternoon or evening interview, send it the following morning. Speed matters because it reinforces your enthusiasm while the conversation is still fresh in everyone's mind.\n"
"\n"
"After your initial thank you email, the next follow-up depends on the timeline the interviewer provided. If they said they would make a decision within two weeks, wait until the end of that two-week period before checking in. Your check-in email should be brief and positive, reaffirming your interest and politely asking for an update on the timeline. Avoid language that suggests impatience or frustration, even if you feel that way internally.\n"
"\n"
"If you do not receive a response to your first follow-up, wait another week before reaching out again. In this second follow-up, keep the tone light and understanding. You might write something like \"I understand that hiring decisions take time, and I wanted to reiterate my strong interest in the role. Please do not hesitate to reach out if you need any additional information from me.\" After two follow-ups with no response, it is generally appropriate to move on and focus your energy on other opportunities.\n"
"\n"
"There are exceptions to these guidelines. If the interviewer specifically asked you to send additional materials, such as a portfolio, writing sample, or references, send those within twenty-four hours along with your thank you note. If you receive another job offer and need to make a decision, it is appropriate to inform the employer about your timeline so they can expedite their process if they are interested in hiring you."
msgstr ""
"Timing is critical in the follow-up process, and getting it right requires a balance between showing interest and respecting boundaries. The thank you email should be sent within twenty-four hours, ideally on the same day as the interview. If you interviewed in the morning, send it by the afternoon. If you had an afternoon or evening interview, send it the following morning. Speed matters because it reinforces your enthusiasm while the conversation is still fresh in everyone's mind.\n"
"\n"
"After your initial thank you email, the next follow-up depends on the timeline the interviewer provided. If they said they would make a decision within two weeks, wait until the end of that two-week period before checking in. Your check-in email should be brief and positive, reaffirming your interest and politely asking for an update on the timeline. Avoid language that suggests impatience or frustration, even if you feel that way internally.\n"
"\n"
"If you do not receive a response to your first follow-up, wait another week before reaching out again. In this second follow-up, keep the tone light and understanding. You might write something like \"I understand that hiring decisions take time, and I wanted to reiterate my strong interest in the role. Please do not hesitate to reach out if you need any additional information from me.\" After two follow-ups with no response, it is generally appropriate to move on and focus your energy on other opportunities.\n"
"\n"
"There are exceptions to these guidelines. If the interviewer specifically asked you to send additional materials, such as a portfolio, writing sample, or references, send those within twenty-four hours along with your thank you note. If you receive another job offer and need to make a decision, it is appropriate to inform the employer about your timeline so they can expedite their process if they are interested in hiring you."

