#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"Treat your job search like a job itself, with dedicated hours, a structured schedule, and clear deliverables for each day. If you are searching full-time, allocate four to six hours per day to search activities. If you are searching while employed, dedicate one to two hours per day, typically in the morning before work or in the evening.\n"
"\n"
"Divide your time across four main categories: prospecting (researching companies and identifying opportunities), applying (tailoring resumes and cover letters for specific positions), networking (reaching out to contacts, attending events, conducting informational interviews), and skill building (taking courses, earning certifications, or completing projects that strengthen your candidacy).\n"
"\n"
"A sample daily schedule for a full-time job seeker might allocate the first hour to reviewing new job postings and company research, the next two hours to tailoring and submitting applications, the fourth hour to networking outreach and follow-ups, and the remaining time to skill building or interview preparation. Adjust the proportions based on where you are in your search, increasing networking time if applications are not generating interviews.\n"
"\n"
"Build in structured breaks and non-search activities to prevent burnout. Exercise, social activities, and hobbies are not distractions from your job search but are essential components of maintaining the mental health and energy required to present your best self in interviews. Many successful job seekers report that their best opportunities came during periods when they maintained balance rather than obsessing over the search.\n"
"\n"
"End each day by writing down three specific things you accomplished and three specific things you will do tomorrow. This simple habit creates momentum, prevents the feeling of unproductive days, and ensures you start each morning with a clear plan rather than staring at a blank screen wondering what to do."
msgstr ""
"Treat your job search like a job itself, with dedicated hours, a structured schedule, and clear deliverables for each day. If you are searching full-time, allocate four to six hours per day to search activities. If you are searching while employed, dedicate one to two hours per day, typically in the morning before work or in the evening.\n"
"\n"
