#: src/data/wiki/categories/job-search-strategies.ts
msgid ""
"What gets measured gets improved, and your job search is no exception. Track key metrics that reveal the health and effectiveness of your search strategy. The most important metrics are application-to-interview conversion rate, interview-to-offer conversion rate, response rate from networking outreach, and time-to-response for each application.\n"
"\n"
"Use a spreadsheet or dedicated application tracking tool to log every application with the company name, position title, date applied, application method (direct, referral, recruiter), follow-up dates, and current status. This data reveals patterns that inform strategic adjustments. If you are applying to 50 positions and getting zero interviews, the problem is likely in your resume or application targeting. If you are getting interviews but no offers, the issue is in your interview performance.\n"
"\n"
"Calculate your conversion rates weekly. A healthy application-to-interview rate is typically 10 to 20 percent for targeted applications. If your rate is below 5 percent, your resume likely needs revision, your targeting may be too broad, or you may be applying to positions where you do not meet the core qualifications. A healthy interview-to-offer rate is 20 to 30 percent, meaning one offer for every three to five final interviews.\n"
"\n"
"Track the source of your interviews to identify which channels are most productive. Many professionals discover that networking and referrals generate a disproportionate share of their interviews despite accounting for a smaller percentage of their overall search effort. This data helps you reallocate time from low-yield channels to high-yield ones.\n"
"\n"
"Review your metrics biweekly and make strategic adjustments. If direct applications are not working, increase your networking efforts. If a particular industry is not responding, explore adjacent industries. If your resume is not generating callbacks, invest time in professional resume review. Data-driven adjustments are more effective than gut feelings or random changes."
msgstr ""
"What gets measured gets improved, and your job search is no exception. Track key metrics that reveal the health and effectiveness of your search strategy. The most important metrics are application-to-interview conversion rate, interview-to-offer conversion rate, response rate from networking outreach, and time-to-response for each application.\n"
