#: src/data/wiki/categories/resume-formats.ts
msgid ""
"Your career stage is one of the most important factors in determining the right resume format. The needs and challenges of a recent graduate are fundamentally different from those of a mid-career professional or a senior executive, and your resume format should reflect your current position on this spectrum.\n"
"\n"
"Entry-level candidates and recent graduates typically have limited professional experience but may have relevant internships, academic projects, volunteer work, and extracurricular activities. A chronological resume works well if you have enough entries to fill the work experience section. If your experience is thin, a combination format allows you to lead with your skills and academic achievements while still listing any work experience you have. Avoid the functional format at this stage, as it may suggest you have something to hide.\n"
"\n"
"Early-career professionals with two to five years of experience should generally use the chronological format. At this stage, you have enough work history to tell a career story, and recruiters want to see how you have been growing professionally. Your resume should demonstrate increasing responsibility and developing expertise. If you are making an early career change, a combination format can help you pivot by highlighting transferable skills alongside your work history.\n"
"\n"
"Mid-career professionals with five to fifteen years of experience have more options. If your career has followed a clear upward trajectory, the chronological format remains the strongest choice. If you have diverse experience or are transitioning to a new field, the combination format gives you the flexibility to lead with your most relevant qualifications. At this stage, your resume should be results-oriented, with quantified achievements that demonstrate the impact you have made.\n"
"\n"
"Senior professionals and executives with fifteen or more years of experience often benefit from the combination format because it allows them to highlight strategic competencies while still demonstrating career progression. At the executive level, your resume should focus on leadership, vision, organizational impact, and business results. A two-page resume is standard at this level, and a brief \"Early Career\" section can cover positions from more than fifteen years ago without detailed descriptions.\n"
"\n"
"Career changers at any stage should seriously consider the combination format. It allows you to present your transferable skills prominently while providing the work history context that builds credibility. Your professional summary should explicitly address the transition, framing your background as an asset rather than a liability.\n"
"\n"
"Professionals re-entering the workforce after a gap should evaluate the combination format or, in some cases, the functional format. The combination format is generally safer because it still includes a work history section. Use your professional summary to briefly and positively explain your career break, focusing on what you did during the gap that kept your skills current, such as freelance work, volunteering, continuing education, or professional development."
