#: src/data/wiki/categories/cover-letters.ts
msgid ""
"Your cover letter and resume are two distinct documents with different purposes, yet many candidates use the cover letter simply to restate their resume in paragraph form. This is a wasted opportunity that adds no value to your application. If the hiring manager reads your cover letter and learns nothing new, they have no additional reason to be interested in you.\n"
"\n"
"A resume is a factual summary of your qualifications -- job titles, dates, bullet-pointed achievements, and skills. A cover letter, by contrast, is a narrative document that provides context, motivation, and personality. It should answer questions your resume cannot: Why are you interested in this specific role? What drove you to make particular career decisions? How do your diverse experiences come together to make you uniquely qualified?\n"
"\n"
"Instead of repeating that you \"managed a team of 12 engineers,\" your cover letter should explain what you learned about leadership from that experience and how it prepared you for the challenges of the role you are applying for. Instead of listing your technical skills again, describe a specific project where you applied those skills to solve a meaningful problem and what the results meant for the business.\n"
"\n"
"Think of your resume as the \"what\" and your cover letter as the \"why\" and \"how.\" Together, they should paint a complete picture of you as a candidate. The hiring manager should finish reading both documents feeling like they understand not just your qualifications, but your motivations, your thought process, and your potential for growth."
msgstr ""
