#: src/data/wiki/categories/career-transitions.ts
msgid ""
"Your freelance career has given you a broader professional network than most traditional employees have. Leveraging this network strategically is one of the most effective ways to find and secure a full-time position.\n"
"\n"
"Your existing clients are your most valuable networking resource. If you have clients whose organizations you admire, let them know you are interested in full-time opportunities. Many freelancers transition to full-time roles with former clients, as these employers already know the quality of your work and your ability to integrate with their team. Even if your current clients do not have openings, they may refer you to colleagues at other organizations.\n"
"\n"
"Reconnect with colleagues you have met through project work, coworking spaces, industry events, and professional communities. Let your network know that you are actively seeking a full-time position and what type of role you are looking for. Be specific about your goals so that people can make targeted introductions. A message like \"I am looking for a senior product design role at a mid-size SaaS company in the fintech space\" is far more actionable than \"I am looking for a full-time job.\"\n"
"\n"
"Update your LinkedIn profile to reflect your transition goals. Your headline should signal your interest in full-time opportunities while highlighting your expertise. Something like \"Senior UX Designer | 8 Years of Design Leadership Across 50+ Projects | Open to Full-Time Opportunities\" tells recruiters exactly what you offer and what you are looking for.\n"
"\n"
"Attend industry events and meetups regularly. As a freelancer, you may have focused on client acquisition at these events. Shift your mindset to networking for employment. Build relationships with hiring managers, team leads, and recruiters in your target industry. The personal connections you make can bypass the applicant tracking system and put your resume directly in front of decision-makers."
